2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout: NAME:
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    cloudflared tunnel - Use Cloudflare Tunnel to expose private services to the Internet or to Cloudflare connected private users.
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout: USAGE:
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    cloudflared tunnel command [command options]  
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout: DESCRIPTION:
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    Cloudflare Tunnel allows to expose private services without opening any ingress port on this machine. It can expose:
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:      A) Locally reachable HTTP-based private services to the Internet on DNS with Cloudflare as authority (which you can
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    then protect with Cloudflare Access).
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:      B) Locally reachable TCP/UDP-based private services to Cloudflare connected private users in the same account, e.g.,
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    those enrolled to a Zero Trust WARP Client.
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    You can manage your Tunnels via one.dash.cloudflare.com. This approach will only require you to run a single command
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    later in each machine where you wish to run a Tunnel.
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    Alternatively, you can manage your Tunnels via the command line. Begin by obtaining a certificate to be able to do so:
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:      $ cloudflared tunnel login
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    With your certificate installed you can then get started with Tunnels:
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:      $ cloudflared tunnel create my-first-tunnel
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:      $ cloudflared tunnel route dns my-first-tunnel my-first-tunnel.mydomain.com
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:      $ cloudflared tunnel run --hello-world my-first-tunnel
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    You can now access my-first-tunnel.mydomain.com and be served an example page by your local cloudflared process.
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    For exposing local TCP/UDP services by IP to your privately connected users, check out:
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:      $ cloudflared tunnel route ip --help
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    See https://developers.cloudflare.com/cloudflare-one/connections/connect-apps/install-and-setup/tunnel-guide/ for more info.
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout: COMMANDS:
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    login      Generate a configuration file with your login details
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    create     Create a new tunnel with given name
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    route      Define which traffic routed from Cloudflare edge to this tunnel: requests to a DNS hostname, to a Cloudflare Load Balancer, or traffic originating from Cloudflare WARP clients
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    vnet       Configure and query virtual networks to manage private IP routes with overlapping IPs.
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    run        Proxy a local web server by running the given tunnel
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    list       List existing tunnels
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    ready      Call /ready endpoint and return proper exit code
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    info       List details about the active connectors for a tunnel
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    delete     Delete existing tunnel by UUID or name
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    cleanup    Cleanup tunnel connections
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    token      Fetch the credentials token for an existing tunnel (by name or UUID) that allows to run it
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    diag       Creates a diagnostic report from a local cloudflared instance
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    proxy-dns  dns-proxy feature is no longer supported
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    help, h    Shows a list of commands or help for one command
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout: OPTIONS:
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    --config value           Specifies a config file in YAML format.
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    --origincert value       Path to the certificate generated for your origin when you run cloudflared login. [%TUNNEL_ORIGIN_CERT%]
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    --autoupdate-freq value  Autoupdate frequency. Default is 24h0m0s. (default: 24h0m0s)
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    --no-autoupdate          Disable periodic check for updates, restarting the server with the new version. (default: false) [%NO_AUTOUPDATE%]
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    --no-prechecks           Skip connectivity pre-checks at startup. (default: false) [%TUNNEL_NO_PRECHECKS%]
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    --metrics value          Listen address for metrics reporting. If no address is passed cloudflared will try to bind to [localhost:20241 localhost:20242 localhost:20243 localhost:20244 localhost:20245].
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout: If all are unavailable, a random port will be used. Note that when running cloudflared from an virtual
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout: environment the default address binds to all interfaces, hence, it is important to isolate the host
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout: and virtualized host network stacks from each other (default: "localhost:0") [%TUNNEL_METRICS%]
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    --pidfile value                                     Write the application's PID to this file after first successful connection. [%TUNNEL_PIDFILE%]
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    --url URL                                           Connect to the local webserver at URL. (default: "http://localhost:8080") [%TUNNEL_URL%]
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    --hello-world                                       Run Hello World Server (default: false) [%TUNNEL_HELLO_WORLD%]
2026-07-03 11:08:27 - cloudflared stdout:    --socks5 --url                                      specify if this tunnel is running as a SOCK5 Server This flag only takes effect if you define your origin with --url and if you do not use ingress rules. The recommended way is to rely on ingress rules and define this property under `originRequest` as per https://developers.cloudflare.com/cloudflare-one/connections/connect-apps/configuration/configuration-file/ingress (default: false) [%TUNNEL_SOCKS%]
